  "prompt": "Which is the shortest completed cricket Test match?",
  "response": "The shortest completed Test match in terms of balls bowled since records have been extensively maintained is the match between Australia and South Africa at Melbourne in February 1932. The match lasted just 656 balls (or 10 hours of play over two days), with Australia winning by an innings and 72 runs. South Africa's two innings were completed in 491 balls (or just over 81.5 six-ball overs) combined, while Australia batted for 165 balls (27.3 six-ball overs). Matches post-World War II may have other instances but this is the often-cited example from earlier records.",
